<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
I posted this on the VN boards but thought I'd post it here as well to see what you guys knew about this...<P>----------------------------------------<P>I'm sure most of you understand how (standard) mob agro works in DAoC already, but for those of you who don't, here it is in a nutshell: When you attack a mob or move inside of a mob's agro radius, you effectively have just been added to the mob's agro list. In addition, anyone else that is grouped with you has been added to the mob's agro list as well. Each person on the mob's agro list has a different "level" of agro. This dictates who the mob is attacking at any given time. Players can raise their level of agro with the mob by doing various things such as inflicting damage, healing group members, and using special combat styles. <P>Amnesia spells work by resetting everyone's agro level on the mob's agro list back to zero. It does not remove anyone from the agro list, just sets everyone in it to zero. Obviously, I don't know what scale Mythic uses in the code to track levels of agro, but let's assume for the sake of the argument that it starts at zero for lowest level of agro, and starts going up from there. Once amnesia has been cast on a mob, it will continue to attack the player it was attacking before the spell was cast, but now any person in the group who performs an action that draws even the slightest amount of agro will get the mob's agro. Amnesia is an essential tool in the CC player's arsenal. <P>Ok, now that we have that out of the way I'll get to the point of my post. I discovered last night that you can totally wipe a mob's agro list. In other words, you can not only reset everyone's agro level to zero, you can remove everyone from the mob's agro list entirely, to the point where the mob will return to it's spawn point! <P>Now keep in mind, I have done very little testing on this so I'm not sure in how many situations this will work. I'm not even sure how useful this really is, but I did find it interesting. If this is common knowledge then I apologize for sounding like an idiot, but I have a level 40 sorc and a level 47 armsman main and I've never seen this done before or heard anyone talk about it. <P>Does anyone else out there know about this, and if so, is it a bug or as designed? I'll defer telling everyone how to do it just yet until I find out if it's a bug or as designed. It is very easy to do and can be done quickly. I'd hate for them to nerf this cool trick I just learned!
</FONT>
